	<Language_en_US>
		<Row Tag="TXT_KEY_BUILDING_AMERICAN_FACTORY">
			<Text>Steel Mill</Text>
		</Row>
		<Row Tag="TXT_KEY_BUILDING_AMERICAN_FACTORY_STRATEGY">
			<Text>The Steel Mill is an American Unique Building, replacing the Factory. The Steel Mill greatly increases the [ICON_PRODUCTION] Production of a city. Each Steel Mill provides 5 [ICON_RES_STEEL] Steel. The city must already possess a Workshop. 1 [ICON_RES_COAL] Coal is consumed when a Steel Mill is created.</Text>
		</Row>
		<Row Tag="TXT_KEY_BUILDING_AMERICAN_FACTORY_HELP">
			<Text>Provides 5 [ICON_RES_STEEL] Steel. Each source of [ICON_RES_IRON] Iron and [ICON_RES_COAL] Coal worked by this City produces +3 [ICON_PRODUCTION] Production and +3 [ICON_GOLD] Gold.[NEWLINE][NEWLINE]Requires 1 [ICON_RES_COAL] Coal. [COLOR_WARNING_TEXT]Steel is also required.[ENDCOLOR]</Text>
		</Row>
		<Row Tag="TXT_KEY_CIV5_BUILDINGS_AMERICAN_FACTORY_TEXT">
			<Text>A steel mill is an industrial plant for the manufacture of steel. From 1875 to 1920 American steel production grew from 380,000 tons to 60 million tons annually, making the U.S. by far the dominant world leader. A key element was the easy availability of iron ore, coal, and manpower. Iron ore of fair quality was abundant in the eastern states, but the Lake Superior region contained huge deposits of exceedingly rich ore. This iron ore was shipped through the Lakes to ports such as Chicago, Detroit, Cleveland, Erie and Buffalo for shipment by rail to the steel mills. Abundant coal was available in Pennsylvania and Ohio.</Text>
		</Row>
	</Language_en_US>
